15 - Comments: ["I currently don't use public transit very often primarily because the stops are not where I am going. Even when they are, my next reason would be cost and finally that I can't rely on the buses to get there in a timely fashion. When I was a student at Pitt, I took the bus nearly every day between home (same place I live now) and Oakland. The stops were rather convenient and I had several route options (3) with varying walk times that were acceptable. The only way I was able to afford that was because of the free fare through Pitt. \n\nOn another note, Pittsburgh is one of the ONLY metropolitan areas I have been to in the world that does not have reliable and easy-to-use transit to the airport. While I believe that it is important to develop and support routes for people who are unable to afford NOT to take the bus to school and work (it is a luxury to be able to own my own car and pay for a ride share if necessary), having reliable transportation to the airport would do a lot for Pittsburgh as a city and the region as a whole. "]

15 - Comments:
["Better cross town service would be very helpful.  Increasing the frequency of the 64 bus and/or creating a route from squirrel hill to East liberty would be great.

I commute from squirrel hill to 3500 technology drive in Monroeville.  If the 67 bus went there after the Monroeville mall there is a good chance I would commute by bus some or most of the time.  Especially if the bus were faster and/or more frequent.

Parking limitations at the Monroeville mall are a capacity limitation that would limit the usefulness of more frequent busses if that is not addressed.  Since there is no overnight parking people can't take the bus to the train station or airport."]

15 - Comments:
["I'm content with public transit for my daily work commute from Churchill into downtown Pittsburgh, but when it comes to traveling for work to other areas of Allegheny County, running errands (e.g., grocery shopping and retail shopping), visiting family, or going to my place of worship, I don't feel like I have as many direct options in terms of public transit from where I live. I'm fortunate enough to have a car that I can use to get to those places with ease, and I actually prefer to drive in most cases, but I know that others are not so fortunate.

The area that I strongly believe needs a connection to the P67 line is the Churchill Valley area of Penn Hills. I have known several people who walk along unsafe, unpaved sides of roads along Rodi Road for 30 minutes to get to the P67 stop at William Penn Highway and Rodi Road. I also go to the Penn Hills shopping center once a week to run errands. I believe Rodi Road had a bus route on that strip in the past, but no longer does, and it would be great to see it come back.

Thank you also for your beautifully designed website, infographics, and interactive maps! Props to everyone involved! It was a pleasure to learn about your initiative and take this survey."]

15 - Comments: ['Please consider (re-consider) the concept of smaller community busses.  Monroeville used to have a "Gold Bus" specifically to transport people to grocery stores, malls, and hospitals in the area.  I am a supporter of public transportation but it is very inconvenient in the East Suburbs.  I have to drive to a bus stop (Monroeville Mall or Penn Center) and because I am going to Oakland don\'t have the option of a flyer bus.  Therefore I leave my house at 8 AM to arrive at Pitt in time for 10 AM classes.  Wait times back to Monroeville for the 67 or 69 routes are typically 45 minutes or more (they appear to run only once per hour). Perhaps a commuter rail from the east suburbs should be considered or electric buses?']

12 - Why Other Transport Used: ['The stops/stations are hard to get to because of bad or no sidewalks', 'I usually need to carry too many things']
15 - Comments:
['My family uses a mix of transit and private vehicles to get around - typically we drive to one of the parking garages adjacent to a T station and take the T to our work and my son's Downtown daycare. On occasions that we need to split up or go at different times, we can use the East Busway because we live somewhat close to the Wilkinsburg station.

However, getting to and from the busway from the Park Place section of Pittsburgh can be difficult, especially with a small child. The station itself could use better pedestrian connections (this was made harder when the stair from the south side of Penn Ave was closed), but with the large parking lots and intervening parcels I don't know how this could be accomplished without redeveloping things. There are "flyer" routes that leave the busway at the Wilkinsburg ramps and get a little closer on neighborhood streets but they are rare outside of the standard commute times.

We'd look to an East Busway expansion as an opportunity to do more of our shopping and errands to the east (Edgewood, Monroeville, the Waterfront) via transit. ']

15 - Comments: ["While I selfishly want to be able to get to where I work and play by transit more easily and more often by transit, a lot of those places are already rather well served by transit. I think it's important to reduce congestion in often-visited places, certainly, but I also think it's important to introduce better transit to areas that haven't historically had it. Every time we cut a bus line to a poor community, we disenfranchise people. I'd like to see transit conducted in a way that can be considered a long-term investment in communities that need to retain young residents/promote business growth, etc."]
